<subsection xml:id="subsec-Expressing-composite-numbers-as-a-product-of-prime-factors">
    <title>Expressing composite numbers as a product of prime factors</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Composite numbers are numbers that has more than two factors,meaning it can be divided 
            evenly by numbers other than <m>1</m> and itself.
        </p>
        <p>
            Process of breaking a composite number is prime factorization and prime factorization expresses 
            the number as the product of prime numbers.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <!-- factors subsubsection -->
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-Factors-of-composite-numbers">
        <title>Factors of composite numbers</title>
        <p>
            Factors are numbers that can divide a given number without leaving a remainder.
            Factors are also called divisors.
        </p>
        <p>
            Tumaini school is planning a sports day and Kamau needs to organize students into equal-sized teams.
            There are <m>24</m> students in his class. Kamau needs factors of <m>24</m> to divide the students 
            into equal teams so that no one is left out.
        </p>
        <p>
            Since the factors of <m>24</m> are <m>1,2,3,4,6,8,12</m> and <m>24</m>. 
            It gives Kamau possible ways to divide the students into equally.
        </p>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    List all the factors of each of the following numbers.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a)" cols="2">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>40</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>84</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>40</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                To determine the factors of <m>40</m>, 
                                we need to identify all numbers between <m>1</m> and <m>40</m> that
                                divide <m>40</m> exactly, leaving no remainder.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                We check the divisibility of each number step by step:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>1</m> divides <m>40</m> exactly: <m>40 \div 1 = 40</m>. 
                                            Therefore, <m>1</m> is a factor of <m>40</m>.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>2</m> divides <m>40</m> exactly: <m>40 \div 2 = 20</m>.
                                            Therefore, <m>2</m> is a factor of <m>40</m>.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>3</m> does not divide <m>40</m> exactly: <m>40 \div 3 = 13</m> with a remainder of <m>1</m>.
                                            Therefore, <m>3</m> is not a factor of <m>40</m>.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>4</m> divides <m>40</m> exactly: <m>40 \div 4 = 10</m>. 
                                            Therefore, <m>4</m> is a factor of <m>40</m>.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ul>  
                            </p>

                            <p>
                                We continue this process for other numbers to check if they divide <m>40</m> without leaving a remainder.
                            </p>

                            <p>
                                After completing the checks, we find that <m>1, 2, 4, 5, 8, 10, 20,</m> and <m>40</m> all divide <m>40</m> exactly.
                            </p>

                            <p>
                                Therefore, the factors of <m>40</m> are <m>1, 2, 4, 5, 8, 10, 20,</m> and <m>40</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>84</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Another way to find the factors of a number is by identifying pairs of numbers that, when multiplied together, produce that number. 
                                If <m>a \times b = c</m>, then both <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are factors of <m>c</m>.
                            </p>

                            <p>
                                To determine the factors of <m>84</m>, we find all pairs of numbers whose product equals <m>84</m>:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li><p><m>1 \times 84 = 84</m></p></li>
                                    <li><p><m>2 \times 42 = 84</m></p></li>
                                    <li><p><m>3 \times 28 = 84</m></p></li>
                                    <li><p><m>4 \times 21 = 84</m></p></li>
                                    <li><p><m>6 \times 14 = 84</m></p></li>
                                    <li><p><m>7 \times 12 = 84</m></p></li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Since we have identified all factor pairs of <m>84</m>, we can list its factors as follows:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                The factors of <m>84</m> are <m>1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 7, 12, 14, 21, 28, 42,</m> and <m>84</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Exercise for Factors goes here.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
    </subsubsection>

