        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Express <m>48</m> as a product of its prime factors.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p> 
                    To break down <m>48</m> into its prime factors, we need to find which prime numbers multiply together to give us <m>48</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Remember:</alert> Always start with the smallest prime number (which is <m>2</m>). 
                    If the number isn’t divisible by <m>2</m>, move to the next prime number 
                    (<m>3</m>, then <m>5</m>, and so on) until you can’t divide further.
                </p>
                 <p> 
                    We start with the smallest prime number, which is <m>2</m>. 
                    Let's divide <m>48</m> by <m>2</m>: <m>48 \div 2 = 24</m>.
                     Since it divides exactly, <m>2</m> is our first prime factor. 

                 </p>
                <p> 
                    Next, we take <m>24</m> and divide it by <m>2</m> again: <m>24 \div 2 = 12</m>. 
                    It divides exactly, so <m>2</m> is our second prime factor. 
                </p> 
                <p> 
                    Now, we take <m>12</m> and divide it by <m>2</m> once more: <m>12 \div 2 = 6</m>. It divides exactly, so <m>2</m> is our third prime factor. 
                </p>
                <p> 
                    Next, we take <m>6</m> and divide it by <m>2</m> again: <m>6 \div 2 = 3</m>. It divides exactly, so <m>2</m> is our fourth prime factor.
                 </p>
                <p> 
                    Finally, we have <m>3</m>, which is already a prime number and cannot be divided further.
                 </p>
                <p> 
                    So, the prime factors of <m>48</m> are: <m>48 = 2 \times 2 \times 2 \times 2 \times 3</m>. 
                </p>
                    <tabular>
                        <row  bottom="medium"> 
                            <cell right="medium"><m>{\color{blue}2}</m></cell>
                            <cell right="medium"><m>48</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell right="medium"><m>{\color{blue}2}</m></cell>
                            <cell right="medium">24</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell right="medium"><m>{\color{blue}2}</m></cell>
                            <cell right="medium">12</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell right="medium"><m>{\color{blue}2}</m></cell>
                            <cell right="medium">6</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell right="medium"><m>{\color{blue}2}</m></cell>
                            <cell right="medium">3</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell right="medium"><m>{\color{blue}3}</m></cell>
                            <cell right="medium">1</cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                <p>
                    <m>48 = 2 \times 2 \times 2 \times 2 \times 3</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Express <m>88</m> as a product of its prime factors.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p> 
                    To find the prime factors of <m>88</m>, we will use a factor tree. 
                    A factor tree helps us break down a composite number into its prime factors step by step. 
                </p> 
                <p> 
                    Here’s how the factor tree for <m>88</m> looks:
                </p>
                <image width="25%">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    <latex-image label="factors-of-88">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[level distance=1.5cm,
                            level 1/.style={sibling distance=2cm},
                            level 2/.style={sibling distance=1cm},
                            circled/.style={draw, circle}]
                            \node {88}
                                child {node[circled] {2}}
                                child {node {44}
                                child {node[circled] {2}}
                                child {node {22}
                                    child {node[circled] {2}}
                                    child {node[circled] {11}}}};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                <p> 
                    We start by breaking <m>88</m> into <m>2</m> and <m>44</m>. 
                    Then, <m>44</m> is broken into <m>2</m> and <m>22</m>, and
                    finally, <m>22</m> is broken into <m>2</m> and <m>11</m>.
                    Since <m>11</m> is a prime number, we stop here. 
                </p> 
                <p>
                    We can't factor any more, so we have found the prime factors.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, the product of prime factors of <m>88</m> is : <m>88 = 2 \times 2 \times 2 \times 11 </m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
